style="border-width:0; margin-bottom:12px;"
src="https://i.creativecommons.org/l/by-nc-sa/4.0/88x31.png"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</copyright><lastBuildDate>Tue, 21 May 2024 06:11:43 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>Nikola (getnikola.com)</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>La composición de una función creciente y una decreciente es decreciente</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/21-la_composicion_de_una_funcion_creciente_y_una_decreciente_es_decreciente/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Sea una función \(f\) de \(ℝ\) en \(ℝ\). Se dice que \(f\) es &lt;strong&gt;creciente&lt;/strong&gt; si para todo \(x\) e \(y\) tales que \(x ≤ y\) se tiene que \(f(x) ≤ f(y)\). Se dice que \(f\) es &lt;strong&gt;decreciente&lt;/strong&gt; si para todo \(x\) e \(y\) tales que \(x ≤ y\) se tiene que \(f(x) ≥ f(y)\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que si \(f\) es creciente y \(g\) es decreciente, entonces \(g ∘ f\) es decreciente.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Data.Real.Basic&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;f&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;g&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;ℝ&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;→&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;ℝ&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;def&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;creciente&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;f&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;ℝ&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;→&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;ℝ&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Prop&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="bp"&gt;∀&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;},&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;≤&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;→&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;f&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;≤&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;f&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;def&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;decreciente&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;f&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;ℝ&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;→&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;ℝ&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Prop&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="bp"&gt;∀&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;},&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;≤&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;→&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;f&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;≥&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;f&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;hf&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;creciente&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;f&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;hg&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;decreciente&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;g&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;decreciente&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;g&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;∘&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;f&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;by&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/21-la_composicion_de_una_funcion_creciente_y_una_decreciente_es_decreciente/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 4 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/21-la_composicion_de_una_funcion_creciente_y_una_decreciente_es_decreciente/</guid><pubDate>Tue, 21 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Los monoides booleanos son conmutativos</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/20-los_monoides_booleanos_son_conmutativos/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Un monoide es un conjunto junto con una operación binaria que es asociativa y tiene elemento neutro.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Un monoide \(M\) es booleano si
\[ (∀ x ∈ M)[x·x = 1] \]
y es conmutativo si
\[ (∀ x, y ∈ M)[x·y = y·x] \]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;En Lean4, está definida la clase de los monoides (como &lt;code&gt;Monoid&lt;/code&gt;) y sus propiedades características son&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;   &lt;span class="n"&gt;mul_assoc&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;c&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;c&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
   &lt;span class="n"&gt;one_mul&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;   &lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;
   &lt;span class="n"&gt;mul_one&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;   &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que los monoides booleanos son conmutativos.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Basic&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Monoid&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;h&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;∀&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;∀&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;by&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/20-los_monoides_booleanos_son_conmutativos/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 7 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/20-los_monoides_booleanos_son_conmutativos/</guid><pubDate>Mon, 20 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Si M es un monoide, a ∈ M y m, n ∈ ℕ, entonces a^(m·n) = (a^m)^n</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/17-potencias_de_potencias_en_monoides/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que si \(M\) es un monoide, \(a ∈ M\) y \(m, n ∈ ℕ\), entonces
\[ a^{m·n} = (a^m)^n \]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Algebra.GroupPower.Basic&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kn"&gt;open&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Nat&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Monoid&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;m&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;n&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;ℕ&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;^&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;m&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;n&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;^&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;m&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;^&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;n&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;by&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/17-potencias_de_potencias_en_monoides/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 5 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/17-potencias_de_potencias_en_monoides/</guid><pubDate>Fri, 17 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Si G es un grupo y a, b, c ∈ G tales que a·b = a·c, entonces b = c</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/16-propiedad_cancelativa_en_grupos/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que si \(G\) es un grupo y \(a, b, c ∈ G\) tales que \(a·b = a·c\), entonces \(b = c\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Basic&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Group&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;c&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;h&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;  &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;c&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;c&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/16-propiedad_cancelativa_en_grupos/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 5 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/16-propiedad_cancelativa_en_grupos/</guid><pubDate>Thu, 16 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Si G un grupo y a ∈ G, entonces (a⁻¹)⁻¹ = a</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/15-inverso_de_inverso_en_grupos/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que si \(G\) un grupo y \(a ∈ G\), entonces
\[(a⁻¹)⁻¹ = a\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Basic&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Group&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;⁻¹&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;⁻¹&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/15-inverso_de_inverso_en_grupos/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 3 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/15-inverso_de_inverso_en_grupos/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 15 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Si G es un grupo y a, b ∈ G, entonces (ab)⁻¹ = b⁻¹a⁻¹</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/14-inverso_del_producto/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que si \(G\) es un grupo y \(a, b \in G\), entonces \((ab)^{-1} = b^{-1}a^{-1}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Defs&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Type&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;_&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Group&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;⁻¹&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;⁻¹&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;⁻¹&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/14-inverso_del_producto/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 3 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/14-inverso_del_producto/</guid><pubDate>Tue, 14 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Si G es un grupo y a, b ∈ G tales que ab = 1 entonces a⁻¹ = b</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/13-unicidad_de_los_inversos_en_los_grupos/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que si \(a\) es un elemento de un grupo \(G\), entonces \(a\) tiene un único inverso; es decir, si \(b\) es un elemento de \(G\) tal que \(a·b = 1\), entonces \(a⁻¹ = b\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Basic&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Group&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;h&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;⁻¹&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;by&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/13-unicidad_de_los_inversos_en_los_grupos/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 3 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/13-unicidad_de_los_inversos_en_los_grupos/</guid><pubDate>Mon, 13 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Unicidad del elemento neutro en los grupos</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/10-unicidad_del_elemento_neutro_en_los_grupos/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que un grupo sólo posee un elemento neutro.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Basic&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Group&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;e&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;G&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;h&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;∀&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;e&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;e&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/10-unicidad_del_elemento_neutro_en_los_grupos/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 1 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/10-unicidad_del_elemento_neutro_en_los_grupos/</guid><pubDate>Fri, 10 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Caracterización de producto igual al primer factor</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/09-caracterizacion_de_producto_igual_al_primer_factor/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Un monoide cancelativo por la izquierda es un monoide \(M\) que cumple la propiedad cancelativa por la izquierda; es decir, para todo \(a, b ∈ M\)
\[ a·b = a·c ↔ b = c \]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;En Lean4 la clase de los monoides cancelativos por la izquierda es &lt;code&gt;LeftCancelMonoid&lt;/code&gt; y la propiedad cancelativa por la izquierda es&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;   &lt;span class="n"&gt;mul_left_cancel&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;c&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;→&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;c&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que si \(M\) es un monoide cancelativo por la izquierda y \(a, b ∈ M\), entonces
\[ a·b = a ↔ b = 1 \]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Basic&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;LeftCancelMonoid&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;a&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;↔&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;by&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/09-caracterizacion_de_producto_igual_al_primer_factor/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 3 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/09-caracterizacion_de_producto_igual_al_primer_factor/</guid><pubDate>Thu, 09 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Unicidad de inversos en monoides</title><link>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/08-unicidad_de_inversos_en_monoides/</link><dc:creator>José A. Alonso</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Demostrar con Lean4 que si \(M\) es un monoide conmutativo y \(x, y, z ∈ M\) tales que \(x·y = 1\) y \(x·z = 1\), entonces \(y = z\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Para ello, completar la siguiente teoría de Lean4:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre class="code literal-block"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Basic&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kt"&gt;Type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;CommMonoid&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;variable&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;z&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="kd"&gt;example&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;hy&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;hz&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;z&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="o"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="bp"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;z&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;:=&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="kd"&gt;by&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="gr"&gt;sorry&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/08-unicidad_de_inversos_en_monoides/"&gt;Leer más…&lt;/a&gt; (quedan 3 minutos de lectura)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://jaalonso.github.io/calculemus/posts/2024/05/08-unicidad_de_inversos_en_monoides/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 08 May 2024 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>